# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dask-parallel
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dask-parallel/array] Dask Array implements a subset of the NumPy ndarray interface using blocked algorithms, cutting up the large array into many small arrays.
[src:dask-parallel/array] This lets us compute on arrays larger than memory using all of our cores.
[src:dask-parallel/array] We coordinate these blocked algorithms using Dask graphs.
[src:dask-parallel/array] Dask Array is used across a wide variety of applications — anywhere where working with large array dataset.
[src:dask-parallel/array] This Analyzing the National Water Model with Xarray, Dask, and Coiled example process 6 TB of geospatial data on a cluster using Xarray and Dask Array.
[src:dask-parallel/array] The cluster in this example is deployed with Coiled, but there are many options for managing and deploying Dask.
[src:dask-parallel/array] See our Deploy Dask Clusters documentation for more information on deployment options.
[src:dask-parallel/array] You can also visit https://examples.dask.org/array.html for a collection of additional examples.
[src:dask-parallel/array] Dask arrays coordinate many NumPy arrays (or “duck arrays” that are sufficiently NumPy-like in API such as CuPy or Sparse arrays) arranged into a grid.
[src:dask-parallel/array] These arrays may live on disk or on other machines.
[src:dask-parallel/array] New duck array chunk types (types below Dask on NEP-13’s type-casting hierarchy) can be registered via `register_chunk_type()`.
[src:dask-parallel/array] Any other duck array types that are not registered will be deferred to in binary operations and NumPy ufuncs/functions (that is, Dask will return `NotImplemented`).
[src:dask-parallel/array] Note, however, that *any* ndarray-like type can be inserted into a Dask Array using `from_array()`.
[src:dask-parallel/array] Dask Array is used in fields like atmospheric and oceanographic science, large scale imaging, genomics, numerical algorithms for optimization or statistics, and more.
[src:dask-parallel/array] However, Dask Array does not implement the entire NumPy interface.
[src:dask-parallel/array] Users expecting this will be disappointed.
[src:dask-parallel/array] See the dask.array API for a more extensive list of functionality.
[src:dask-parallel/array] By default, Dask Array uses the threaded scheduler in order to avoid data transfer costs, and because NumPy releases the GIL well.
[src:dask-parallel/array] It is also quite effective on a cluster using the dask.distributed scheduler.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] It is easy to get started with Dask’s APIs, but using them *well* requires some experience.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This page contains suggestions for Dask best practices and includes solutions to common Dask problems.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This document specifically focuses on best practices that are shared among all of the Dask APIs.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Readers may first want to investigate one of the API-specific Best Practices documents first.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Parallelism brings extra complexity and overhead.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Sometimes it’s necessary for larger problems, but often it’s not.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Dask’s dashboard helps you to understand the state of your workers.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This information can help to guide you to efficient solutions.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] In parallel and distributed computing there are new costs to be aware of and so your old intuition may no longer be true.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Working with the dashboard can help you relearn about what is fast and slow and how to deal with it.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] See Documentation on Dask’s dashboard for more information.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Your chunks of data should be small enough so that many of them fit in a worker’s available memory at once.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] You often control this when you select partition size in Dask DataFrame (see DataFrame Partitions) or chunk size in Dask Array (see Array Chunks).
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Dask will likely manipulate as many chunks in parallel on one machine as you have cores on that machine.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] So if you have 1 GB chunks and ten cores, then Dask is likely to use *at least* 10 GB of memory.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Additionally, it’s common for Dask to have 2-3 times as many chunks available to work on so that it always has something to work on.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] If you have a machine with 100 GB and 10 cores, then you might want to choose chunks in the 1GB range.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] You have space for ten chunks per core which gives Dask a healthy margin, without having tasks that are too small.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Note that you also want to avoid chunk sizes that are too small.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] For a more detailed guide to choosing chunk sizes for Dask Arrays, see this blog post on Choosing good chunk sizes.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] A task is a Python function, like `np.sum` applied onto a Python object, like a pandas DataFrame or NumPy array.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] If you are working with Dask collections with many partitions, then every operation you do, like `x + 1` likely generates many tasks, at least as many as partitions in your collection.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This is somewhere between 200us and 1ms.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] If you have a computation with thousands of tasks this is fine, there will be about a second of overhead, and that may not trouble you.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] However when you have very large graphs with millions of tasks then this may become troublesome, both because overhead is now in the 10 minutes to hours range, and also because the overhead of dealing with such a large graph can start to overwhelm the scheduler.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] The high level Dask collections (array, DataFrame, bag) include common operations that follow standard Python APIs from NumPy and pandas.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] However, many Python workloads are complex and may require operations that are not included in these high level APIs.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] As your ability to compute increases you will likely find that data access and I/O take up a larger portion of your total time.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Additionally, parallel computing will often add new constraints to how your store your data, particularly around providing random access to blocks of your data that are in line with how you plan to compute on it.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] If you’re doing mostly numeric work with Numpy, pandas, Scikit-learn, Numba, and other libraries that release the GIL, then use mostly threads.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] If you’re doing work on text data or Python collections like lists and dicts then use mostly processes.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] If you’re on larger machines with a high thread count (much greater than 4), then you should probably split things up into at least a few processes regardless.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Python can be highly productive with about 4 threads per process with numeric work, but not 50 threads.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This is advise that generalizes to cloud computing and picking appropriate VM instance sizes.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] There is a lot of nuance to picking the _perfect_ instance but a good starting point is a 1:4 CPU to RAM ratio with one Worker instance per VM.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] You can adjust from there given your workload.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] For more information on threads, processes, and how to configure them in Dask, see the scheduler documentation.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] A common anti-pattern we see is people creating large Python objects like a DataFrame or an Array on the client (i.e. their local machine) outside of Dask and then embedding them into the computation.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This means that Dask has to send these objects over the network multiple times instead of just passing pointers to the data.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This incurs a lot of overhead and slows down a computation quite significantly, especially so if the network connection between the client and the scheduler is slow.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] It can also overload the scheduler so that it errors with out of memory errors.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Instead, you should use Dask methods to load the data and use Dask to control the results.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] We are using Dask to read a parquet dataset before appending a set of pandas DataFrames to it.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] We are loading the csv files into memory before sending the data to Dask.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Instead, we can use Dask to read the csv files directly, keeping all data on the cluster.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] We are using NumPy to create an in-memory array before handing it over to Dask, forcing Dask to embed the array into the task graph instead of handling pointers to the data.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Instead, we can use Dask to read the file directly, keeping all data on the cluster.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] We are using pandas to read a large CSV file before building a Graph with delayed to parallelize a computation on the data.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Instead, we can use delayed to read the data as well.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This avoid embedding the large file into the graph, Dask can just pass a reference to the delayed object around.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Embedding large objects like pandas DataFrames or Arrays into the computation is a frequent pain point for Dask users.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] It adds a significant delay until the scheduler has received and is able to start the computation and stresses the scheduler during the computation.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Using Dask to load these objects instead avoids these issues and improves the performance of a computation significantly.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] Calling `compute` will block the execution on the client until the Dask computation completes.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] A pattern we regularly see is users calling `compute` in a loop or sequentially on slightly different queries.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This prohibits Dask from parallelizing different computations on the cluster and from sharing intermediate results between different queries.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This holds execution every time that the iteration arrives at the compute call computing one query at a time.
[src:dask-parallel/best-practices] This allows Dask to compute the shared parts of the computation (like the `foo` object above) only once, rather than once per `compute` call and allows Dask to parallelize across the different selects as well instead of running them sequentially.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask was created by Matthew Rocklin in December 2014 and has over 9.8k stars and 500 contributors on GitHub.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask is used by retail, financial, governmental organizations, as well as life science and geophysical institutes.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Walmart, Wayfair, JDA, GrubHub, General Motors, Nvidia, Harvard Medical School, Capital One and NASA are among the organizations that use Dask.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask's high-level parallel collections – DataFrames, Bags, and Arrays – operate in parallel on datasets that may not fit into memory.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask's task scheduler executes task graphs in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] This powers the high-level collections as well as custom, user-defined workloads using low-level collections.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Under the hood, each of these user interfaces adopts the same parallel computing machinery.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask's high-level collections are the natural entry point for users who are interested in scaling up their pandas, NumPy or scikit-learn workload.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask's DataFrame, Array and Dask-ML are alternatives to Pandas DataFrame, Numpy Array and scikit-learn respectively with slight variations to the original interfaces.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask Array is a high-level collection that parallelizes array-based workloads and maintains the familiar NumPy API, such as slicing, arithmetic, reductions, mathematics, etc., making it easy for Numpy users to scale up array operations.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] A Dask array comprises many smaller n-dimensional Numpy arrays and uses a blocked algorithm to enable computation on larger-than-memory arrays.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] During an operation, Dask translates the array operation into a task graph, breaks up large Numpy arrays into multiple smaller chunks, and executes the work on each chunk in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Results from each chunk are combined to produce the final output.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask DataFrame is a high-level collection that parallelizes DataFrame based workloads.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] A Dask DataFrame comprises many smaller Pandas DataFrames partitioned along the index.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] It maintains the familiar Pandas API, making it easy for Pandas users to scale up DataFrame workloads.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] During a DataFrame operation, Dask creates a task graph and triggers operations on the constituent DataFrames in a manner that reduces memory footprint and increases parallelism through sharing and deleting of intermediate results.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask Bag is an unordered collection of repeated objects, a hybrid between a set and a list.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask Bag is used to parallelize computation of semi-structured or unstructured data, such as JSON records, text data, log files or user-defined Python objects using operations such as filter, fold, map and groupby.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask Bags can be created from an existing Python iterable or can load data directly from text files and binary files in the Avro format.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] The Dask low-level interface allows for more customization.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] It is suitable for data that does not fall within the scope of a Dask DataFrame, Bag or Array.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask delayed is an interface used to parallelize generic Python code that does not fit into high level collections like Dask Array or Dask DataFrame.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Python functions decorated with Dask delayed adopt a lazy evaluation strategy by deferring execution and generating a task graph with the function and its arguments.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] The Python function will only execute when .compute is invoked.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask delayed can be used as a function dask.delayed or as a decorator @dask.delayed.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask Futures, an immediate (non-lazy) alternative to Dask delayed, provides a real-time task framework that extends Python's concurrent.futures interface, which provides a high-level interface for asynchronous execution of callables.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] It is common to combine high and low-level interfaces.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] For example, users can run Dask array/bag/dataframe to load and pre-process data, then switch to Dask delayed for a custom algorithm that is specific to their domain, then switch back to Dask array/dataframe to clean up and store results.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask's high and low-level collections create a directed acyclic graph of tasks, which represents the relationship between computation tasks.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] A node in a task graph represents a Python function that performs a unit of computation and an edge represents the data dependency between the upstream and downstream task.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] After a task graph is generated, the task scheduler manages the workflow based on the given task graph by assigning tasks to workers in a manner that improves parallelism and respects the data dependencies.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask provides **two families of schedulers**: single-machine scheduler and distributed scheduler.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] A single-machine scheduler is the default scheduler which provides basic features on local processes or thread pool and is meant to be used on a single machine.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] It is simple and cheap to use but does not scale.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] A threaded scheduler leverages Python's concurrent.futures.ThreadPoolExecuter to execute computations.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] It has a low memory footprint and does not require any setup.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] As all the computations occur in the same process, threaded schedulers incur minimal task overhead and no cost from transfer of data between tasks.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] scheduler leverages Python's concurrent.futures.ProcessPoolExecutor to execute computations.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Tasks and its dependencies are transferred from the main process to a local process, executed, and the results are transferred back to the main process.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] This allows bypassing of issues with Python's Global Interpretable Lock and provides parallelism for computation tasks with primarily Python code.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] However, transferring data between the main and local processes degrades performance, especially in cases when the size of data transferred is large.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] A single threaded scheduler executes computation with no parallelism.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask's distributed scheduler can be set up on a local machine or scale out on a cluster.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask can work with resource managers, such as Hadoop YARN, Kubernetes, or PBS, Slurm, SGD and LSF for High Performance Computing (HPC) clusters.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask-ML is compatible with scikit-learn's estimator API of fit, transform and predict and is well integrated with machine learning and deep learning frameworks such XGBoost, LightGBM, PyTorch, Keras, and TensorFlow through scikit-learn compatible wrappers.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Selected scikit-learn estimators and utilities can be parallelized through executing jobs across multiple CPU cores using the Joblib library.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] The number of processes are determined by the n_jobs parameters.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] By default, the Joblib library uses loky as its multi-processing back-end.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask offers an alternative Joblib backend which is useful for scaling of Joblib-backed scikit-learn algorithms out to a cluster of machines for compute constrained workloads.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] For memory constrained workloads, Dask offers alternatives, such as Parallel Meta-estimators for parallelizing and scaling out tasks that are not parallelized within scikit-learn and Incremental Hyperparameter Optimization for scaling hyper-parameter search and parallelized estimators.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] XGBoost and LightGBM are popular algorithms that are based on Gradient Boosting and both are integrated with Dask for distributed learning.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask does not power XGBoost or LightGBM, rather it facilitates setting up of the cluster, scheduler, and workers required then hands off the data to the machine learning framework to perform distributed training.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Training an XGBoost model with Dask, a Dask cluster is composed of a central scheduler and multiple distributed workers, is accomplished by spinning up an XGBoost scheduler in the same process running the Dask central scheduler and XGBoost worker in the same process running the Dask workers.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask workers then hand over the Pandas DataFrame to the local XGBoost worker for distributed training.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Skorch is a scikit-learn compatible wrapper for PyTorch, which enables Dask-ML to be used together with PyTorch.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] SciKeras is an scikit-learn compatible wrapper for Keras models which enables Dask-ML to be used with Keras.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask is used for high resolution, 4-dimensional, cellular imagery by Harvard Medical School, Howard Hughes Medical Institute, Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, and the UC Berkeley Advanced Bioimaging Center.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] They record the evolution and movements of a 3-dimensional cell over time, in maximum detail.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] This generates large amounts of data that is difficult to analyze with traditional methods.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask helps them scale their data analysis workflows with its API that resembles NumPy, Pandas, and scikit-learn code.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask is also used at the Novartis Institute for Biomedical Research to scale machine learning prototypes.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask is used in Climate Science, Energy, Hydrology, Meteorology, and Satellite Imaging by companies such as NASA, LANL, PANGEO: Earth Science and the UK Meteorology Office.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Oceanographers produce massive simulated datasets of the Earth's oceans and researchers can look at large seismology datasets from sensors around the world, collect a large number of observations from satellites and weather stations, and run big simulations.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask is integrated into many libraries, such as Pangeo and xarray; time series software like Prophet and tsfresh; ETL/ML software like scikit-learn, RAPIDS, and XGBoost; workflow management tools like Apache Airflow and Prefect.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask was originally developed at Continuum Analytics, a for-profit Python consulting company that eventually became Anaconda, Inc., the creator of many open-source packages and the Anaconda Python distribution.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask grew out of the Blaze project, a DARPA funded project to accelerate computation in open source.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Blaze was an ambitious project that tried to redefine computation, storage, compression, and data science APIs for Python, led originally by Travis Oliphant and Peter Wang, the co-founders of Anaconda.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] However, Blaze's approach of being an ecosystem-in-a-package meant that it was harder for new users to easily adopt.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Instead of rewriting a software ecosystem, Dask's team intended to augment the existing one with the right component.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] With this idea in mind, on December 21, 2014 Matthew Rocklin created Dask.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] The purpose of Dask was originally to parallelize NumPy so that it could use one full workstation computer, which was common in finance shops at the time.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] The first projects to really adopt Dask were Xarray(commonly used in geo sciences) and Scikit-Image (commonly used in image processing).
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask was integrated into Xarray within a few months of being created.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] It provided Dask with its first user community, which remains to this day.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Understanding that there is demand for a lightweight parallelism solution for Pandas DataFrames and machine learning tools, such as scikit-learn, Dask quickly evolved to support other projects as well.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Since 2018, other teams and institutions in academia, tech companies, and large corporations such as NASA, UK Met Office, Blue Yonder and Nvidia, became interested in Dask and began integrating it into their systems.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] Dask received support from a diverse set of sources: the US Government (DARPA grant), the Gordon and Betty Moore Foundation, Anaconda, NSF, NASA (US research grants with collaborations like Pangeo) and Nvidia.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] In 2020, Matthew Rocklin founded Coiled Computing, Inc. to provide further support for Dask development and enable companies to deploy Dask clusters in the cloud.
[src:dask-parallel/dask-software] In May 2021, the company raised $21 million in series A funding led by Bessemer Venture Partners.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] Dask DataFrame helps you process large tabular data by parallelizing pandas, either on your laptop for larger-than-memory computing, or on a distributed cluster of computers.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] Dask DataFrames coordinate many pandas DataFrames/Series arranged along the index.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] A Dask DataFrame is partitioned *row-wise*, grouping rows by index value for efficiency.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] These pandas objects may live on disk or on other machines.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] Pandas and Dask have the same API, and so switching from one to the other is straightforward.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] Dask is lazy; when you want an in-memory result add `.compute()`.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] Machine learning libraries often have Dask submodules that expect Dask DataFrames and operate in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] As with all Dask collections, you trigger computation by calling the `.compute()` method or persist data in distributed memory with the `.persist()` method.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] There are simpler ways to accelerate your computation, like avoiding `.apply` or Python for loops and using a built-in pandas method instead.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] Dask DataFrame is used across a wide variety of applications — anywhere where working with large tabular dataset.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] These examples all process larger-than-memory datasets on Dask clusters deployed with Coiled, but there are many options for managing and deploying Dask.
[src:dask-parallel/dataframe] You can also visit https://examples.dask.org/dataframe.html for a collection of additional examples.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The components of a distributed system communicate and coordinate their actions by passing messages to one another in order to achieve a common goal.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Three challenges of distributed systems are: maintaining concurrency of components, overcoming the lack of a global clock, and managing the independent failure of components.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] When a component of one system fails, the entire system does not fail.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Examples of distributed systems vary from SOA-based systems to microservices to massively multiplayer online games to peer-to-peer applications.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Distributed systems cost more than monolithic architectures, primarily due to increased needs for additional hardware, servers, gateways, firewalls, new subnets, proxies, and so on.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Distributed systems can also suffer from fallacies of distributed computing.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Conversely, a well-designed distributed system is more scalable, more durable, more changeable, and more fine-tuned than a monolithic application deployed on a single machine.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] According to Marc Brooker: "a system is scalable in the range where marginal cost of additional workload is nearly constant." Serverless technologies fit this definition but the total cost of ownership, and not just the infrastructure cost must be considered.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] A computer program that runs within a distributed system is called a **distributed program**, and *distributed programming* is the process of writing such programs.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] There are many types of implementations for the message-passing mechanism, including pure HTTP, RPC-like connectors, and message queues.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The word *distributed* in terms such as "distributed system", "distributed programming", and "distributed algorithm" originally referred to computer networks where individual computers were physically distributed within some geographical area.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The terms are nowadays used in a much wider sense, even referring to autonomous processes that run on the same physical computer and interact with each other by message passing.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] A distributed system may have a common goal, such as solving a large computational problem; the user then perceives the collection of autonomous processors as a unit.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Alternatively, each computer may have its own user with individual needs, and the purpose of the distributed system is to coordinate the use of shared resources or provide communication services to the users.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In distributed systems, events represent a fact or state change (e.g., *OrderPlaced*) and are typically broadcast asynchronously to multiple consumers, promoting loose coupling and scalability.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] While events generally don't expect an immediate response, acknowledgment mechanisms are often implemented at the infrastructure level (e.g., Kafka commit offsets, SNS delivery statuses) rather than being an inherent part of the event pattern itself.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In contrast, messages serve a broader role, encompassing commands (e.g., *ProcessPayment*), events (e.g., *PaymentProcessed*), and documents (e.g., *DataPayload*).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Both events and messages can support various delivery guarantees, including at-least-once, at-most-once, and exactly-once, depending on the technology stack and implementation.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] However, exactly-once delivery is often achieved through idempotency mechanisms rather than true, infrastructure-level exactly-once semantics.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Delivery patterns for both events and messages include publish/subscribe (one-to-many) and point-to-point (one-to-one).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] While request/reply is technically possible, it is more commonly associated with messaging patterns rather than pure event-driven systems.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Events excel at state propagation and decoupled notifications, while messages are better suited for command execution, workflow orchestration, and explicit coordination.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Modern architectures commonly combine both approaches, leveraging events for distributed state change notifications and messages for targeted command execution and structured workflows based on specific timing, ordering, and delivery requirements.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Distributed systems are groups of networked computers which share a common goal for their work.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have much overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The same system may be characterized both as "parallel" and "distributed"; the processors in a typical distributed system run concurrently in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Parallel computing may be seen as a particularly tightly coupled form of distributed computing, and distributed computing may be seen as a loosely coupled form of parallel computing.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The figure on the right illustrates the difference between distributed and parallel systems.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Figure (a) is a schematic view of a typical distributed system; the system is represented as a network topology in which each node is a computer and each line connecting the nodes is a communication link.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Figure (b) shows the same distributed system in more detail: each computer has its own local memory, and information can be exchanged only by passing messages from one node to another by using the available communication links.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Figure (c) shows a parallel system in which each processor has a direct access to a shared memory.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The situation is further complicated by the traditional uses of the terms parallel and distributed *algorithm* that do not quite match the above definitions of parallel and distributed *systems* (see below for more detailed discussion).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Nevertheless, as a rule of thumb, high-performance parallel computation in a shared-memory multiprocessor uses parallel algorithms while the coordination of a large-scale distributed system uses distributed algorithms.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The use of concurrent processes which communicate through message-passing has its roots in operating system architectures studied in the 1960s.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The first widespread distributed systems were local-area networks such as Ethernet, which was invented in the 1970s.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] ARPANET, one of the predecessors of the Internet, was introduced in the late 1960s, and ARPANET e-mail was invented in the early 1970s.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] E-mail became the most successful application of ARPANET, and it is probably the earliest example of a large-scale distributed application.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In addition to ARPANET (and its successor, the global Internet), other early worldwide computer networks included Usenet and FidoNet from the 1980s, both of which were used to support distributed discussion systems.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The study of distributed computing became its own branch of computer science in the late 1970s and early 1980s.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The first conference in the field, Symposium on Principles of Distributed Computing (PODC), dates back to 1982, and its counterpart International Symposium on Distributed Computing (DISC) was first held in Ottawa in 1985 as the International Workshop on Distributed Algorithms on Graphs.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Various hardware and software architectures are used for distributed computing.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] At a lower level, it is necessary to interconnect multiple CPUs with some sort of network, regardless of whether that network is printed onto a circuit board or made up of loosely coupled devices and cables.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] At a higher level, it is necessary to interconnect processes running on those CPUs with some sort of communication system.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Distributed programming typically falls into one of several basic architectures: client–server, three-tier, *n*-tier, or peer-to-peer; or categories: loose coupling, or tight coupling.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Another basic aspect of distributed computing architecture is the method of communicating and coordinating work among concurrent processes.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Through various message passing protocols, processes may communicate directly with one another, typically in a main/sub relationship.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Alternatively, a "database-centric" architecture can enable distributed computing to be done without any form of direct inter-process communication, by utilizing a shared database.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Database-centric architecture in particular provides relational processing analytics in a schematic architecture allowing for live environment relay.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] This enables distributed computing functions both within and beyond the parameters of a networked database.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture is a distributed computing approach in which computational resources are organized into self-contained units called cells.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Each cell operates independently, processing requests while maintaining scalability, fault isolation, and availability.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] A cell typically consists of multiple services or application components and functions as an autonomous unit.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Some implementations replicate entire sets of services across multiple cells, while others partition workloads between cells.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In replicated models, requests may be rerouted to an operational cell if another experiences a failure.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] This design is intended to enhance system resilience by reducing the impact of localized failures.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Some implementations employ circuit breakers within and between cells.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Within a cell, circuit breakers may be used to prevent cascading failures among services, while inter-cell circuit breakers can isolate failing cells and redirect traffic to those that remain operational.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Cell-based architecture has been adopted in some large-scale distributed systems, particularly in cloud-native and high-availability environments, where fault isolation and redundancy are key design considerations.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Its implementation varies depending on system requirements, infrastructure constraints, and operational objectives.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] According to Reactive Manifesto, reactive distributed systems are responsive, resilient, elastic and message-driven.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Subsequently, Reactive systems are more flexible, loosely-coupled and scalable.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] To make your systems reactive, you are advised to implement Reactive Principles.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Reactive Principles are a set of principles and patterns which help to make your cloud native application as well as edge native applications more reactive.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Many tasks that we would like to automate by using a computer are of question–answer type: we would like to ask a question and the computer should produce an answer.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In theoretical computer science, such tasks are called computational problems.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Formally, a computational problem consists of *instances* together with a *solution* for each instance.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Instances are questions that we can ask, and solutions are desired answers to these questions.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Theoretical computer science seeks to understand which computational problems can be solved by using a computer (computability theory) and how efficiently (computational complexity theory).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Traditionally, it is said that a problem can be solved by using a computer if we can design an algorithm that produces a correct solution for any given instance.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Such an algorithm can be implemented as a computer program that runs on a general-purpose computer: the program reads a problem instance from input, performs some computation, and produces the solution as output.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Formalisms such as random-access machines or universal Turing machines can be used as abstract models of a sequential general-purpose computer executing such an algorithm.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The field of concurrent and distributed computing studies similar questions in the case of either multiple computers, or a computer that executes a network of interacting processes: which computational problems can be solved in such a network and how efficiently?
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] However, it is not at all obvious what is meant by "solving a problem" in the case of a concurrent or distributed system: for example, what is the task of the algorithm designer, and what is the concurrent or distributed equivalent of a sequential general-purpose computer?
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The discussion below focuses on the case of multiple computers, although many of the issues are the same for concurrent processes running on a single computer.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In the case of distributed algorithms, computational problems are typically related to graphs.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Often the graph that describes the structure of the computer network *is* the problem instance.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] This is illustrated in the following example.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Consider the computational problem of finding a coloring of a given graph *G*.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] While the field of parallel algorithms has a different focus than the field of distributed algorithms, there is much interaction between the two fields.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] For example, the Cole–Vishkin algorithm for graph coloring was originally presented as a parallel algorithm, but the same technique can also be used directly as a distributed algorithm.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Moreover, a parallel algorithm can be implemented either in a parallel system (using shared memory) or in a distributed system (using message passing).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The traditional boundary between parallel and distributed algorithms (choose a suitable network vs. run in any given network) does not lie in the same place as the boundary between parallel and distributed systems (shared memory vs. message passing).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In parallel algorithms, yet another resource in addition to time and space is the number of computers.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Indeed, often there is a trade-off between the running time and the number of computers: the problem can be solved faster if there are more computers running in parallel (see speedup).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] If a decision problem can be solved in polylogarithmic time by using a polynomial number of processors, then the problem is said to be in the class NC.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The class NC can be defined equally well by using the PRAM formalism or Boolean circuits—PRAM machines can simulate Boolean circuits efficiently and vice versa.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In the analysis of distributed algorithms, more attention is usually paid on communication operations than computational steps.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Perhaps the simplest model of distributed computing is a synchronous system where all nodes operate in a lockstep fashion.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] This model is commonly known as the LOCAL model.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] During each *communication round*, all nodes in parallel (1) receive the latest messages from their neighbours, (2) perform arbitrary local computation, and (3) send new messages to their neighbors.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In such systems, a central complexity measure is the number of synchronous communication rounds required to complete the task.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] This complexity measure is closely related to the diameter of the network.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] On the one hand, any computable problem can be solved trivially in a synchronous distributed system in approximately 2*D* communication rounds: simply gather all information in one location (*D* rounds), solve the problem, and inform each node about the solution (*D* rounds).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] On the other hand, if the running time of the algorithm is much smaller than *D* communication rounds, then the nodes in the network must produce their output without having the possibility to obtain information about distant parts of the network.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In other words, the nodes must make globally consistent decisions based on information that is available in their *local D-neighbourhood*.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Many distributed algorithms are known with the running time much smaller than *D* rounds, and understanding which problems can be solved by such algorithms is one of the central research questions of the field.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Typically an algorithm which solves a problem in polylogarithmic time in the network size is considered efficient in this model.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Another commonly used measure is the total number of bits transmitted in the network (cf. communication complexity).
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The features of this concept are typically captured with the CONGEST(B) model, which is similarly defined as the LOCAL model, but where single messages can only contain B bits.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Traditional computational problems take the perspective that the user asks a question, a computer (or a distributed system) processes the question, then produces an answer and stops.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] However, there are also problems where the system is required not to stop, including the dining philosophers problem and other similar mutual exclusion problems.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In these problems, the distributed system is supposed to continuously coordinate the use of shared resources so that no conflicts or deadlocks occur.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] There are also fundamental challenges that are unique to distributed computing, for example those related to *fault-tolerance*.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Examples of related problems include consensus problems, Byzantine fault tolerance, and self-stabilisation.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Note that in distributed systems, latency should be measured through "99th percentile" because "median" and "average" can be misleading.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The network nodes communicate among themselves in order to decide which of them will get into the "coordinator" state.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] For that, they need some method in order to break the symmetry among them.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] For example, if each node has unique and comparable identities, then the nodes can compare their identities, and decide that the node with the highest identity is the coordinator.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The definition of this problem is often attributed to LeLann, who formalized it as a method to create a new token in a token ring network in which the token has been lost.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Coordinator election algorithms are designed to be economical in terms of total bytes transmitted, and time.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The algorithm suggested by Gallager, Humblet, and Spira for general undirected graphs has had a strong impact on the design of distributed algorithms in general, and won the Dijkstra Prize for an influential paper in distributed computing.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Many other algorithms were suggested for different kinds of network graphs, such as undirected rings, unidirectional rings, complete graphs, grids, directed Euler graphs, and others.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] A general method that decouples the issue of the graph family from the design of the coordinator election algorithm was suggested by Korach, Kutten, and Moran.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In order to perform coordination, distributed systems employ the concept of coordinators.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The coordinator election problem is to choose a process from among a group of processes on different processors in a distributed system to act as the central coordinator.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] Several central coordinator election algorithms exist.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] So far the focus has been on *designing* a distributed system that solves a given problem.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] A complementary research problem is *studying* the properties of a given distributed system.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The halting problem is an analogous example from the field of centralised computation: we are given a computer program and the task is to decide whether it halts or runs forever.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] The halting problem is undecidable in the general case, and naturally understanding the behaviour of a computer network is at least as hard as understanding the behaviour of one computer.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] However, there are many interesting special cases that are decidable.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] In particular, it is possible to reason about the behaviour of a network of finite-state machines.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] One example is telling whether a given network of interacting (asynchronous and non-deterministic) finite-state machines can reach a deadlock.
[src:dask-parallel/distributed-computing] This problem is PSPACE-complete, i.e., it is decidable, but not likely that there is an efficient (centralised, parallel or distributed) algorithm that solves the problem in the case of large networks.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The model is a specialization of the *split-apply-combine* strategy for data analysis.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] It is inspired by the map and reduce functions commonly used in functional programming, although their purpose in the MapReduce framework is not the same as in their original forms.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] As such, a single-threaded implementation of MapReduce is usually not faster than a traditional (non-MapReduce) implementation; any gains are usually only seen with multi-threaded implementations on multi-processor hardware.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The use of this model is beneficial only when the optimized distributed shuffle operation (which reduces network communication cost) and fault tolerance features of the MapReduce framework come into play.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Optimizing the communication cost is essential to a good MapReduce algorithm.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce libraries have been written in many programming languages, with different levels of optimization.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] A popular open-source implementation that has support for distributed shuffles is part of Apache Hadoop.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The name MapReduce originally referred to the proprietary Google technology, but has since become a generic trademark.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] By 2014, Google was no longer using MapReduce as its primary *big data* processing model, and development on Apache Mahout had moved on to more capable and less disk-oriented mechanisms that incorporated full map and reduce capabilities.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Processing can occur on data stored either in a filesystem (unstructured) or in a database (structured).
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce can take advantage of the locality of data, processing it near the place it is stored in order to minimize communication overhead.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] **Shuffle:** worker nodes redistribute data based on the output keys (produced by the `map` function), such that all data belonging to one key is located on the same worker node.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] **Reduce:** worker nodes now process each group of output data, per key, in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce allows for the distributed processing of the map and reduction operations.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Maps can be performed in parallel, provided that each mapping operation is independent of the others; in practice, this is limited by the number of independent data sources and/or the number of CPUs near each source.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Similarly, a set of 'reducers' can perform the reduction phase, provided that all outputs of the map operation that share the same key are presented to the same reducer at the same time, or that the reduction function is associative.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The parallelism also offers some possibility of recovering from partial failure of servers or storage during the operation: if one mapper or reducer fails, the work can be rescheduled – assuming the input data are still available.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Map() code** – Map() is run exactly once for each *K1* key, generating output organized by key *K2*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] **"Shuffle" the Map output to the Reduce processors** – the MapReduce system designates Reduce processors, assigns the *K2* key each processor should work on, and provides that processor with all the Map-generated data associated with that key.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] **Run the user-provided Reduce() code** – Reduce() is run exactly once for each *K2* key produced by the Map step.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] **Produce the final output** – the MapReduce system collects all the Reduce output, and sorts it by *K2* to produce the final outcome.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] These five steps can be logically thought of as running in sequence – each step starts only after the previous step is completed – although in practice they can be interleaved as long as the final result is not affected.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In many situations, the input data might have already been distributed ("sharded") among many different servers, in which case step 1 could sometimes be greatly simplified by assigning Map servers that would process the locally present input data.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Similarly, step 3 could sometimes be sped up by assigning Reduce processors that are as close as possible to the Map-generated data they need to process.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Map* and *Reduce* functions of *MapReduce* are both defined with respect to data structured in (key, value) pairs.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Map* function is applied in parallel to every pair (keyed by `k1`) in the input dataset.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] This produces a list of pairs (keyed by `k2`) for each call.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] After that, the MapReduce framework collects all pairs with the same key (`k2`) from all lists and groups them together, creating one group for each key.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Each *Reduce* call typically produces either one key value pair or an empty return, though one call is allowed to return more than one key value pair.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The returns of all calls are collected as the desired result list.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Thus the MapReduce framework transforms a list of (key, value) pairs into another list of (key, value) pairs.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] This behavior is different from the typical functional programming map and reduce combination, which accepts a list of arbitrary values and returns one single value that combines *all* the values returned by map.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] It is necessary but not sufficient to have implementations of the map and reduce abstractions in order to implement MapReduce.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Distributed implementations of MapReduce require a means of connecting the processes performing the Map and Reduce phases.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Other options are possible, such as direct streaming from mappers to reducers, or for the mapping processors to serve up their results to reducers that query them.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Here, each document is split into words, and each word is counted by the *map* function, using the word as the result key.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The framework puts together all the pairs with the same key and feeds them to the same call to *reduce*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Thus, this function just needs to sum all of its input values to find the total appearances of that word.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] As another example, imagine that for a database of 1.1 billion people, one would like to compute the average number of social contacts a person has according to age.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Note that in the Reduce function, C is the count of people having in total N contacts, so in the Map function it is natural to write C=1, since every output pair is referring to the contacts of one single person.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The MapReduce system would line up the 1100 Map processors, and would provide each with its corresponding 1 million input records.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The Map step would produce 1.1 billion (Y,(N,1)) records, with Y values ranging between, say, 8 and 103.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The MapReduce System would then line up the 96 Reduce processors by performing shuffling operation of the key/value pairs due to the fact that we need average per age, and provide each with its millions of corresponding input records.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The Reduce step would result in the much reduced set of only 96 output records (Y,A), which would be put in the final result file, sorted by Y.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The count info in the record is important if the processing is reduced more than one time.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] If we reduce it with file #3, we lose the count of how many records we've already seen, so we end up with an average of 9.5 contacts for a 10-year-old person ((9+10)/2), which is wrong.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Software framework architecture adheres to open-closed principle where code is effectively divided into unmodifiable *frozen spots* and extensible *hot spots*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The frozen spot of the MapReduce framework is a large distributed sort.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *input reader* divides the input into appropriate size 'splits' (in practice, typically, 64 MB to 128 MB) and the framework assigns one split to each *Map* function.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *input reader* reads data from stable storage (typically, a distributed file system) and generates key/value pairs.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] A common example will read a directory full of text files and return each line as a record.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Map* function takes a series of key/value pairs, processes each, and generates zero or more output key/value pairs.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The input and output types of the map can be (and often are) different from each other.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] If the application is doing a word count, the map function would break the line into words and output a key/value pair for each word.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Each output pair would contain the word as the key and the number of instances of that word in the line as the value.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Each *Map* function output is allocated to a particular *reducer* by the application's *partition* function for sharding purposes.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *partition* function is given the key and the number of reducers and returns the index of the desired *reducer*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] A typical default is to hash the key and use the hash value modulo the number of *reducers*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Between the map and reduce stages, the data are *shuffled* (parallel-sorted / exchanged between nodes) in order to move the data from the map node that produced them to the shard in which they will be reduced.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The shuffle can sometimes take longer than the computation time depending on network bandwidth, CPU speeds, data produced and time taken by map and reduce computations.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The input for each *Reduce* is pulled from the machine where the *Map* ran and sorted using the application's *comparison* function.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The framework calls the application's *Reduce* function once for each unique key in the sorted order.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Reduce* can iterate through the values that are associated with that key and produce zero or more outputs.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In the word count example, the *Reduce* function takes the input values, sums them and generates a single output of the word and the final sum.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Output Writer* writes the output of the *Reduce* to the stable storage.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Properties of monoids are the basis for ensuring the validity of MapReduce operations.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In the Algebird package a Scala implementation of Map/Reduce explicitly requires a monoid class type .
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The operations of MapReduce deal with two types: the type *A* of input data being mapped, and the type *B* of output data being reduced.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Map* operation takes individual values of type *A* and produces, for each *a:A* a value *b:B*; The *Reduce* operation requires a binary operation • defined on values of type *B*; it consists of folding all available *b:B* to a single value.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] From a basic requirements point of view, any MapReduce operation must involve the ability to arbitrarily regroup data being reduced.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The second property guarantees that, when parallelized over multiple nodes, the nodes that don't have any data to process would have no impact on the result.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] These two properties amount to having a monoid (*B*, •, *e*) on values of type *B* with operation • and with neutral element *e*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] There's no requirements on the values of type *A*; an arbitrary function *A* → *B* can be used for the *Map* operation.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] This means that we have a catamorphism *A** → (*B*, •, *e*).
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Here *A** denotes a Kleene star, also known as the type of lists over *A*.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The *Shuffle* operation per se is not related to the essence of MapReduce; it's needed to distribute calculations over the cloud.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] It follows from the above that not every binary *Reduce* operation will work in MapReduce.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce programs are not guaranteed to be fast.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The main benefit of this programming model is to exploit the optimized shuffle operation of the platform, and only having to write the *Map* and *Reduce* parts of the program.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In practice, the author of a MapReduce program however has to take the shuffle step into consideration; in particular the partition function and the amount of data written by the *Map* function can have a large impact on the performance and scalability.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Additional modules such as the *Combiner* function can help to reduce the amount of data written to disk, and transmitted over the network.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce applications can achieve sub-linear speedups under specific circumstances.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] When designing a MapReduce algorithm, the author needs to choose a good tradeoff between the computation and the communication costs.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Communication cost often dominates the computation cost, and many MapReduce implementations are designed to write all communication to distributed storage for crash recovery.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In tuning performance of MapReduce, the complexity of mapping, shuffle, sorting (grouping by the key), and reducing has to be taken into account.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The amount of data produced by the mappers is a key parameter that shifts the bulk of the computation cost between mapping and reducing.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Reducing includes sorting (grouping of the keys) which has nonlinear complexity.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Hence, small partition sizes reduce sorting time, but there is a trade-off because having a large number of reducers may be impractical.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The influence of split unit size is marginal (unless chosen particularly badly, say <1MB).
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The gains from some mappers reading load from local disks, on average, is minor.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] For processes that complete quickly, and where the data fits into main memory of a single machine or a small cluster, using a MapReduce framework usually is not effective.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Since these frameworks are designed to recover from the loss of whole nodes during the computation, they write interim results to distributed storage.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] This crash recovery is expensive, and only pays off when the computation involves many computers and a long runtime of the computation.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] A task that completes in seconds can just be restarted in the case of an error, and the likelihood of at least one machine failing grows quickly with the cluster size.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] On such problems, implementations keeping all data in memory and simply restarting a computation on node failures or —when the data is small enough— non-distributed solutions will often be faster than a MapReduce system.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce achieves reliability by parceling out a number of operations on the set of data to each node in the network.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Each node is expected to report back periodically with completed work and status updates.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] If a node falls silent for longer than that interval, the master node (similar to the master server in the Google File System) records the node as dead and sends out the node's assigned work to other nodes.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Individual operations use atomic operations for naming file outputs as a check to ensure that there are not parallel conflicting threads running.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] When files are renamed, it is possible to also copy them to another name in addition to the name of the task (allowing for side-effects).
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The reduce operations operate much the same way.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Because of their inferior properties with regard to parallel operations, the master node attempts to schedule reduce operations on the same node, or in the same rack as the node holding the data being operated on.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] This property is desirable as it conserves bandwidth across the backbone network of the datacenter.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Implementations are not necessarily highly reliable.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] For example, in older versions of Hadoop the *NameNode* was a single point of failure for the distributed filesystem.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Moreover, the MapReduce model has been adapted to several computing environments like multi-core and many-core systems, desktop grids, multi-cluster, volunteer computing environments, dynamic cloud environments, mobile environments, and high-performance computing environments.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] At Google, MapReduce was used to completely regenerate Google's index of the World Wide Web.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] It replaced the old *ad hoc* programs that updated the index and ran the various analyses.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Development at Google has since moved on to technologies such as Percolator, FlumeJava and MillWheel that offer streaming operation and updates instead of batch processing, to allow integrating "live" search results without rebuilding the complete index.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce's stable inputs and outputs are usually stored in a distributed file system.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The transient data are usually stored on local disk and fetched remotely by the reducers.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] David DeWitt and Michael Stonebraker, computer scientists specializing in parallel databases and shared-nothing architectures, have been critical of the breadth of problems that MapReduce can be used for.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] They called its interface too low-level and questioned whether it really represents the paradigm shift its proponents have claimed it is.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] They challenged the MapReduce proponents' claims of novelty, citing Teradata as an example of prior art that has existed for over two decades.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Greg Jorgensen wrote an article rejecting these views.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] Jorgensen asserts that DeWitt and Stonebraker's entire analysis is groundless as MapReduce was never designed nor intended to be used as a database.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] DeWitt and Stonebraker have subsequently published a detailed benchmark study in 2009 comparing performance of Hadoop's MapReduce and RDBMS approaches on several specific problems.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] They concluded that relational databases offer real advantages for many kinds of data use, especially on complex processing or where the data is used across an enterprise, but that MapReduce may be easier for users to adopt for simple or one-time processing tasks.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The MapReduce programming paradigm was also described in Danny Hillis's 1985 thesis intended for use on the Connection Machine, where it was called "xapping/reduction" and relied upon that machine's special hardware to accelerate both map and reduce.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The dialect ultimately used for the Connection Machine, the 1986 StarLisp, had parallel `*map` and `reduce!!`, which in turn was based on the 1984 Common Lisp, which had non-parallel `map` and `reduce` built in.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The tree-like approach that the Connection Machine's hypercube architecture uses to execute `reduce` in $O(\log n)$ time is effectively the same as the approach referred to within the Google paper as prior work.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In 2010 Google was granted what is described as a patent on MapReduce.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The patent, filed in 2004, may cover use of MapReduce by open source software such as Hadoop, CouchDB, and others.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In *Ars Technica*, an editor acknowledged Google's role in popularizing the MapReduce concept, but questioned whether the patent was valid or novel.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] In 2013, as part of its "Open Patent Non-Assertion (OPN) Pledge", Google pledged to only use the patent defensively.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] The patent is expected to expire on 23 December 2026.
[src:dask-parallel/mapreduce] MapReduce tasks must be written as acyclic dataflow programs, i.e. a stateless mapper followed by a stateless reducer, that are executed by a batch job scheduler.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In computer science, **parallelism** and concurrency are two different things: a parallel program uses multiple CPU cores, each core performing a task independently.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] On the other hand, concurrency enables a program to deal with multiple tasks even on a single CPU core; the core switches between tasks (i.e. threads) without necessarily completing each one.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A program can have both, neither or a combination of parallelism and concurrency characteristics.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism, with multi-core and multi-processor computers having multiple processing elements within a single machine, while clusters, MPPs, and grids use multiple computers to work on the same task.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Specialized parallel computer architectures are sometimes used alongside traditional processors, for accelerating specific tasks.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Communication and synchronization between the different subtasks are typically some of the greatest obstacles to getting optimal parallel program performance.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A theoretical upper bound on the speed-up of a single program as a result of parallelization is given by Amdahl's law, which states that it is limited by the fraction of time for which the parallelization can be utilised.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Traditionally, computer software has been written for serial computation.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] To solve a problem, an algorithm is constructed and implemented as a serial stream of instructions.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These instructions are executed on a central processing unit on one computer.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Only one instruction may execute at a time—after that instruction is finished, the next one is executed.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computing, on the other hand, uses multiple processing elements simultaneously to solve a problem.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This is accomplished by breaking the problem into independent parts so that each processing element can execute its part of the algorithm simultaneously with the others.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The processing elements can be diverse and include resources such as a single computer with multiple processors, several networked computers, specialized hardware, or any combination of the above.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Historically parallel computing was used for scientific computing and the simulation of scientific problems, particularly in the natural and engineering sciences, such as meteorology.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This led to the design of parallel hardware and software, and high performance computing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Frequency scaling was the dominant reason for improvements in computer performance from the mid-1980s until 2004.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The runtime of a program is equal to the number of instructions multiplied by the average time per instruction.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Maintaining everything else constant, increasing the clock frequency decreases the average time it takes to execute an instruction.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] An increase in frequency thus decreases runtime for all compute-bound programs.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, power consumption *P* by a chip is given by the equation *P* = *C* × *V* 2 × *F*, where *C* is the capacitance being switched per clock cycle (proportional to the number of transistors whose inputs change), *V* is voltage, and *F* is the processor frequency (cycles per second).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Increases in frequency increase the amount of power used in a processor.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Increasing processor power consumption led ultimately to Intel's May 8, 2004 cancellation of its Tejas and Jayhawk processors, which is generally cited as the end of frequency scaling as the dominant computer architecture paradigm.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] To deal with the problem of power consumption and overheating the major central processing unit (CPU or processor) manufacturers started to produce power efficient processors with multiple cores.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The core is the computing unit of the processor and in multi-core processors each core is independent and can access the same memory concurrently.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Multi-core processors have brought parallel computing to desktop computers.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Thus parallelization of serial programs has become a mainstream programming task.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In 2012 quad-core processors became standard for desktop computers, while servers had 10+ core processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Moore's law predicted that the number of cores per processor would double every 18–24 months.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] By 2023 some processors had over one hundred cores.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Some designs having a mix of performance and efficiency cores (such as ARM's big.LITTLE design) due to thermal and design constraints.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] An operating system can ensure that different tasks and user programs are run in parallel on the available cores.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, for a serial software program to take full advantage of the multi-core architecture the programmer needs to restructure and parallelize the code.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A speed-up of application software runtime will no longer be achieved through frequency scaling, instead programmers will need to parallelize their software code to take advantage of the increasing computing power of multicore architectures.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Optimally, the speedup from parallelization would be linear—doubling the number of processing elements should halve the runtime, and doubling it a second time should again halve the runtime.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, very few parallel algorithms achieve optimal speedup.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Most of them have a near-linear speedup for small numbers of processing elements, which flattens out into a constant value for large numbers of processing elements.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The maximum potential speedup of an overall system can be calculated by Amdahl's law.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law indicates that optimal performance improvement is achieved by balancing enhancements to both parallelizable and non-parallelizable components of a task.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Furthermore, it reveals that increasing the number of processors yields diminishing returns, with negligible speedup gains beyond a certain point.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Amdahl's Law has limitations, including assumptions of fixed workload, neglecting inter-process communication and synchronization overheads, primarily focusing on computational aspect and ignoring extrinsic factors such as data persistence, I/O operations, and memory access overheads.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Gustafson's law and Universal Scalability Law give a more realistic assessment of the parallel performance.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Understanding data dependencies is fundamental in implementing parallel algorithms.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] No program can run more quickly than the longest chain of dependent calculations (known as the critical path), since calculations that depend upon prior calculations in the chain must be executed in order.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, most algorithms do not consist of just a long chain of dependent calculations; there are usually opportunities to execute independent calculations in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Let *P**i* and *P**j* be two program segments.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions describe when the two are independent and can be executed in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] For *P**i*, let *I**i* be all of the input variables and *O**i* the output variables, and likewise for *P**j*.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Violation of the first condition introduces a flow dependency, corresponding to the first segment producing a result used by the second segment.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The second condition represents an anti-dependency, when the second segment produces a variable needed by the first segment.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The third and final condition represents an output dependency: when two segments write to the same location, the result comes from the logically last executed segment.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In this example, instruction 3 cannot be executed before (or even in parallel with) instruction 2, because instruction 3 uses a result from instruction 2.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] It violates condition 1, and thus introduces a flow dependency.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In this example, there are no dependencies between the instructions, so they can all be run in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Bernstein's conditions do not allow memory to be shared between different processes.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] For that, some means of enforcing an ordering between accesses is necessary, such as semaphores, barriers or some other synchronization method.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Subtasks in a parallel program are often called threads.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Some parallel computer architectures use smaller, lightweight versions of threads known as fibers, while others use bigger versions known as processes.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, "threads" is generally accepted as a generic term for subtasks.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Threads will often need synchronized access to an object or other resource, for example when they must update a variable that is shared between them.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Without synchronization, the instructions between the two threads may be interleaved in any order.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] If instruction 1B is executed between 1A and 3A, or if instruction 1A is executed between 1B and 3B, the program will produce incorrect data.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The programmer must use a lock to provide mutual exclusion.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A lock is a programming language construct that allows one thread to take control of a variable and prevent other threads from reading or writing it, until that variable is unlocked.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The thread holding the lock is free to execute its critical section (the section of a program that requires exclusive access to some variable), and to unlock the data when it is finished.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] One thread will successfully lock variable V, while the other thread will be locked out—unable to proceed until V is unlocked again.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This guarantees correct execution of the program.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Locks may be necessary to ensure correct program execution when threads must serialize access to resources, but their use can greatly slow a program and may affect its reliability.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Locking multiple variables using non-atomic locks introduces the possibility of program deadlock.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] An atomic lock locks multiple variables all at once.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] If it cannot lock all of them, it does not lock any of them.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] If two threads each need to lock the same two variables using non-atomic locks, it is possible that one thread will lock one of them and the second thread will lock the second variable.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In such a case, neither thread can complete, and deadlock results.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Many parallel programs require that their subtasks act in synchrony.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Barriers are typically implemented using a lock or a semaphore.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] One class of algorithms, known as lock-free and wait-free algorithms, altogether avoids the use of locks and barriers.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, this approach is generally difficult to implement and requires correctly designed data structures.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Not all parallelization results in speed-up.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Generally, as a task is split up into more and more threads, those threads spend an ever-increasing portion of their time communicating with each other or waiting on each other for access to resources.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Once the overhead from resource contention or communication dominates the time spent on other computation, further parallelization (that is, splitting the workload over even more threads) increases rather than decreases the amount of time required to finish.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This problem, known as parallel slowdown, can be improved in some cases by software analysis and redesign.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Applications are often classified according to how often their subtasks need to synchronize or communicate with each other.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] An application exhibits fine-grained parallelism if its subtasks must communicate many times per second; it exhibits coarse-grained parallelism if they do not communicate many times per second, and it exhibits embarrassing parallelism if they rarely or never have to communicate.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Embarrassingly parallel applications are considered the easiest to parallelize.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Flynn created one of the earliest classification systems for parallel (and sequential) computers and programs, now known as Flynn's taxonomy.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Flynn classified programs and computers by whether they were operating using a single set or multiple sets of instructions, and whether or not those instructions were using a single set or multiple sets of data.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-single-data (SISD) classification is equivalent to an entirely sequential program.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The single-instruction-multiple-data (SIMD) classification is analogous to doing the same operation repeatedly over a large data set.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This is commonly done in signal processing applications.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-single-data (MISD) is a rarely used classification.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] While computer architectures to deal with this were devised (such as systolic arrays), few applications that fit this class materialized.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Multiple-instruction-multiple-data (MIMD) programs are by far the most common type of parallel programs.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Hennessy, "Some machines are hybrids of these categories, of course, but this classic model has survived because it is simple, easy to understand, and gives a good first approximation.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can incur significant overhead in practice, primarily due to the costs associated with merging data from multiple processes.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Specifically, inter-process communication and synchronization can lead to overheads that are substantially higher—often by two or more orders of magnitude—compared to processing the same data on a single thread.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Therefore, the overall improvement should be carefully evaluated.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] From the advent of very-large-scale integration (VLSI) computer-chip fabrication technology in the 1970s until about 1986, speed-up in computer architecture was driven by doubling computer word size—the amount of information the processor can manipulate per cycle.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Increasing the word size reduces the number of instructions the processor must execute to perform an operation on variables whose sizes are greater than the length of the word.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Historically, 4-bit microprocessors were replaced with 8-bit, then 16-bit, then 32-bit microprocessors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This trend generally came to an end with the introduction of 32-bit processors, which has been a standard in general-purpose computing for two decades.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Not until the early 2000s, with the advent of x86-64 architectures, did 64-bit processors become commonplace.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A computer program is, in essence, a stream of instructions executed by a processor.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Without instruction-level parallelism, a processor can only issue less than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC < 1).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *subscalar* processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These instructions can be re-ordered and combined into groups which are then executed in parallel without changing the result of the program.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This is known as instruction-level parallelism.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Advances in instruction-level parallelism dominated computer architecture from the mid-1980s until the mid-1990s.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] All modern processors have multi-stage instruction pipelines.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Each stage in the pipeline corresponds to a different action the processor performs on that instruction in that stage; a processor with an *N*-stage pipeline can have up to *N* different instructions at different stages of completion and thus can issue one instruction per clock cycle (IPC = 1).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *scalar* processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The canonical example of a pipelined processor is a RISC processor, with five stages: instruction fetch (IF), instruction decode (ID), execute (EX), memory access (MEM), and register write back (WB).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The Pentium 4 processor had a 35-stage pipeline.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Most modern processors also have multiple execution units.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] They usually combine this feature with pipelining and thus can issue more than one instruction per clock cycle (IPC > 1).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These processors are known as *superscalar* processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Superscalar processors differ from multi-core processors in that the several execution units are not entire processors (i.e. processing units).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Instructions can be grouped together only if there is no data dependency between them.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Scoreboarding and the Tomasulo algorithm (which is similar to scoreboarding but makes use of register renaming) are two of the most common techniques for implementing out-of-order execution and instruction-level parallelism.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Task parallelisms is the characteristic of a parallel program that "entirely different calculations can be performed on either the same or different sets of data".
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This contrasts with data parallelism, where the same calculation is performed on the same or different sets of data.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Task parallelism involves the decomposition of a task into sub-tasks and then allocating each sub-task to a processor for execution.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The processors would then execute these sub-tasks concurrently and often cooperatively.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Task parallelism does not usually scale with the size of a problem.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Superword level parallelism is a vectorization technique based on loop unrolling and basic block vectorization.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] It is distinct from loop vectorization algorithms in that it can exploit parallelism of inline code, such as manipulating coordinates, color channels or in loops unrolled by hand.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Main memory in a parallel computer is either shared memory (shared between all processing elements in a single address space), or distributed memory (in which each processing element has its own local address space).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed memory refers to the fact that the memory is logically distributed, but often implies that it is physically distributed as well.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed shared memory and memory virtualization combine the two approaches, where the processing element has its own local memory and access to the memory on non-local processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Accesses to local memory are typically faster than accesses to non-local memory.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] On the supercomputers, distributed shared memory space can be implemented using the programming model such as PGAS.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This model allows processes on one compute node to transparently access the remote memory of another compute node.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] All compute nodes are also connected to an external shared memory system via high-speed interconnect, such as Infiniband, this external shared memory system is known as burst buffer, which is typically built from arrays of non-volatile memory physically distributed across multiple I/O nodes.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Computer architectures in which each element of main memory can be accessed with equal latency and bandwidth are known as uniform memory access (UMA) systems.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Typically, that can be achieved only by a shared memory system, in which the memory is not physically distributed.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A system that does not have this property is known as a non-uniform memory access (NUMA) architecture.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed memory systems have non-uniform memory access.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Computer systems (with the exception of Groq's LPUs) make use of caches—small and fast memories located close to the processor which store temporary copies of memory values (nearby in both the physical and logical sense).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computer systems have difficulties with caches that may store the same value in more than one location, with the possibility of incorrect program execution.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These computers require a cache coherency system, which keeps track of cached values and strategically purges them, thus ensuring correct program execution.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Bus snooping is one of the most common methods for keeping track of which values are being accessed (and thus should be purged).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Designing large, high-performance cache coherence systems is a very difficult problem in computer architecture.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] As a result, shared memory computer architectures do not scale and distributed memory systems do.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computers based on interconnected networks need to have some kind of routing to enable the passing of messages between nodes that are not directly connected.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The medium used for communication between the processors is likely to be hierarchical in large multiprocessor machines.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computers can be roughly classified according to the level at which the hardware supports parallelism.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This classification is broadly analogous to the distance between basic computing nodes.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These are not mutually exclusive; for example, clusters of symmetric multiprocessors are relatively common.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A multi-core processor is a processor that includes multiple processing units (called "cores") on the same chip.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] IBM's Cell microprocessor, designed for use in the Sony PlayStation 3, is a prominent multi-core processor.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Each core in a multi-core processor can potentially be superscalar as well—that is, on every clock cycle, each core can issue multiple instructions from one thread.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Simultaneous multithreading (of which Intel's Hyper-Threading is the best known) was an early form of pseudo-multi-coreism.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A processor capable of concurrent multithreading includes multiple execution units in the same processing unit—that is it has a superscalar architecture—and can issue multiple instructions per clock cycle from *multiple* threads.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Temporal multithreading on the other hand includes a single execution unit in the same processing unit and can issue one instruction at a time from *multiple* threads.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A symmetric multiprocessor (SMP) is a computer system with multiple identical processors that share memory and connect via a bus.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Bus contention prevents bus architectures from scaling.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] As a result, SMPs generally do not comprise more than 32 processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Because of the small size of the processors and the significant reduction in the requirements for bus bandwidth achieved by large caches, such symmetric multiprocessors are extremely cost-effective, provided that a sufficient amount of memory bandwidth exists.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A distributed computer (also known as a distributed memory multiprocessor) is a distributed memory computer system in which the processing elements are connected by a network.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed computers are highly scalable.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The terms "concurrent computing", "parallel computing", and "distributed computing" have a lot of overlap, and no clear distinction exists between them.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A cluster is a group of loosely coupled computers that work together closely, so that in some respects they can be regarded as a single computer.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Clusters are composed of multiple standalone machines connected by a network.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] While machines in a cluster do not have to be symmetric, load balancing is more difficult if they are not.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The most common type of cluster is the Beowulf cluster, which is a cluster implemented on multiple identical commercial off-the-shelf computers connected with a TCP/IP Ethernet local area network.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Beowulf technology was originally developed by Thomas Sterling and Donald Becker.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] 87% of all Top500 supercomputers are clusters.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The remaining are Massively Parallel Processors, explained below.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Because grid computing systems (described below) can easily handle embarrassingly parallel problems, modern clusters are typically designed to handle more difficult problems—problems that require nodes to share intermediate results with each other more often.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This requires a high bandwidth and, more importantly, a low-latency interconnection network.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Many historic and current supercomputers use customized high-performance network hardware specifically designed for cluster computing, such as the Cray Gemini network.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] As of 2014, most current supercomputers use some off-the-shelf standard network hardware, often Myrinet, InfiniBand, or Gigabit Ethernet.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A massively parallel processor (MPP) is a single computer with many networked processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] MPPs have many of the same characteristics as clusters, but MPPs have specialized interconnect networks (whereas clusters use commodity hardware for networking).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] MPPs also tend to be larger than clusters, typically having "far more" than 100 processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In an MPP, "each CPU contains its own memory and copy of the operating system and application.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] IBM's Blue Gene/L, the fifth fastest supercomputer in the world according to the June 2009 TOP500 ranking, is an MPP.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Grid computing is the most distributed form of parallel computing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] It makes use of computers communicating over the Internet to work on a given problem.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Because of the low bandwidth and extremely high latency available on the Internet, distributed computing typically deals only with embarrassingly parallel problems.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Most grid computing applications use middleware (software that sits between the operating system and the application to manage network resources and standardize the software interface).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The most common grid computing middleware is the Berkeley Open Infrastructure for Network Computing (BOINC).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Often volunteer computing software makes use of "spare cycles", performing computations at times when a computer is idling.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The ubiquity of the Internet and high-bandwidth networks enabled cloud computing, a model where massively parallel resources are provided as a service.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This paradigm abstracts the underlying hardware, allowing users to access virtualized clusters for scalable workloads without managing physical infrastructure.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Modern distributed ledger protocols apply parallel computing principles to overcome the sequential bottlenecks of traditional blockchains.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] By sharding the state space, newer consensus architectures allow for "massively parallel transaction processing".
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In this model, utilized by protocols such as Cerberus, independent transactions are treated as parallel tasks that can be executed simultaneously on different nodes, rather than being processed serially in a single global block.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Within parallel computing, there are specialized parallel devices that remain niche areas of interest.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] While not domain-specific, they tend to be applicable to only a few classes of parallel problems.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Reconfigurable computing is the use of a field-programmable gate array (FPGA) as a co-processor to a general-purpose computer.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] An FPGA is, in essence, a computer chip that can rewire itself for a given task.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] FPGAs can be programmed with hardware description languages such as VHDL or Verilog.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Several vendors have created C to HDL languages that attempt to emulate the syntax and semantics of the C programming language, with which most programmers are familiar.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The best known C to HDL languages are Mitrion-C, Impulse C, and Handel-C.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Specific subsets of SystemC based on C++ can also be used for this purpose.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] AMD's decision to open its HyperTransport technology to third-party vendors has become the enabling technology for high-performance reconfigurable computing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] General-purpose computing on graphics processing units (GPGPU) is a fairly recent trend in computer engineering research.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] GPUs are co-processors that have been heavily optimized for computer graphics processing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Computer graphics processing is a field dominated by data parallel operations—particularly linear algebra matrix operations.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In the early days, GPGPU programs used the normal graphics APIs for executing programs.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, several new programming languages and platforms have been built to do general purpose computation on GPUs with both Nvidia and AMD releasing programming environments with CUDA and Stream SDK respectively.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Other GPU programming languages include BrookGPU, PeakStream, and RapidMind.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Nvidia has also released specific products for computation in their Tesla series.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The technology consortium Khronos Group has released the OpenCL specification, which is a framework for writing programs that execute across platforms consisting of CPUs and GPUs.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] AMD, Apple, Intel, Nvidia and others are supporting OpenCL.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Several application-specific integrated circuit (ASIC) approaches have been devised for dealing with parallel applications.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Because an ASIC is (by definition) specific to a given application, it can be fully optimized for that application.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] As a result, for a given application, an ASIC tends to outperform a general-purpose computer.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, ASICs are created by UV photolithography.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This process requires a mask set, which can be extremely expensive.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A mask set can cost over a million US dollars.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] (The smaller the transistors required for the chip, the more expensive the mask will be.) Meanwhile, performance increases in general-purpose computing over time (as described by Moore's law) tend to wipe out these gains in only one or two chip generations.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] High initial cost, and the tendency to be overtaken by Moore's-law-driven general-purpose computing, has rendered ASICs unfeasible for most parallel computing applications.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] One example is the PFLOPS RIKEN MDGRAPE-3 machine which uses custom ASICs for molecular dynamics simulation.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A vector processor is a CPU or computer system that can execute the same instruction on large sets of data.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Vector processors have high-level operations that work on linear arrays of numbers or vectors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] An example vector operation is *A* = *B* × *C*, where *A*, *B*, and *C* are each 64-element vectors of 64-bit floating-point numbers.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] They are closely related to Flynn's SIMD classification.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Cray computers became famous for their vector-processing computers in the 1970s and 1980s.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, vector processors—both as CPUs and as full computer systems—have generally disappeared.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Modern processor instruction sets do include some vector processing instructions, such as with Freescale Semiconductor's AltiVec and Intel's Streaming SIMD Extensions (SSE).
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Concurrent programming languages, libraries, APIs, and parallel programming models (such as algorithmic skeletons) have been created for programming parallel computers.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These can generally be divided into classes based on the assumptions they make about the underlying memory architecture—shared memory, distributed memory, or shared distributed memory.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Shared memory programming languages communicate by manipulating shared memory variables.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Distributed memory uses message passing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] POSIX Threads and OpenMP are two of the most widely used shared memory APIs, whereas Message Passing Interface (MPI) is the most widely used message-passing system API.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] One concept used in programming parallel programs is the future concept, where one part of a program promises to deliver a required datum to another part of a program at some future time.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Efforts to standardize parallel programming include an open standard called OpenHMPP for hybrid multi-core parallel programming.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The OpenHMPP directive-based programming model offers a syntax to efficiently offload computations on hardware accelerators and to optimize data movement to/from the hardware memory using remote procedure calls.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The rise of consumer GPUs has led to support for compute kernels, either in graphics APIs (referred to as compute shaders), in dedicated APIs (such as OpenCL), or in other language extensions.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Automatic parallelization of a sequential program by a compiler is the "holy grail" of parallel computing, especially with the aforementioned limit of processor frequency.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Despite decades of work by compiler researchers, automatic parallelization has had only limited success.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Mainstream parallel programming languages remain either explicitly parallel or (at best) partially implicit, in which a programmer gives the compiler directives for parallelization.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] A few fully implicit parallel programming languages exist—SISAL, Parallel Haskell, SequenceL, SystemC (for FPGAs), Mitrion-C, VHDL, and Verilog.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] As a computer system grows in complexity, the mean time between failures usually decreases.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing is a technique whereby the computer system takes a "snapshot" of the application—a record of all current resource allocations and variable states, akin to a core dump—; this information can be used to restore the program if the computer should fail.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Application checkpointing means that the program has to restart from only its last checkpoint rather than the beginning.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] While checkpointing provides benefits in a variety of situations, it is especially useful in highly parallel systems with a large number of processors used in high performance computing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] As parallel computers become larger and faster, we are now able to solve problems that had previously taken too long to run.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Fields as varied as bioinformatics (for protein folding and sequence analysis) and economics have taken advantage of parallel computing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Parallel computing can also be applied to the design of fault-tolerant computer systems, particularly via lockstep systems performing the same operation in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] This provides redundancy in case one component fails, and also allows automatic error detection and error correction if the results differ.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] These methods can be used to help prevent single-event upsets caused by transient errors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Although additional measures may be required in embedded or specialized systems, this method can provide a cost-effective approach to achieve n-modular redundancy in commercial off-the-shelf systems.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The origins of true (MIMD) parallelism go back to Luigi Federico Menabrea and his *Sketch of the Analytic Engine Invented by Charles Babbage*.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1957, Compagnie des Machines Bull announced the first computer architecture specifically designed for parallelism, the Gamma 60.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] It utilized a fork-join model and a "Program Distributor" to dispatch and collect data to and from independent processing units connected to a central memory.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In April 1958, Stanley Gill (Ferranti) discussed parallel programming and the need for branching and waiting.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Also in 1958, IBM researchers John Cocke and Daniel Slotnick discussed the use of parallelism in numerical calculations for the first time.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Burroughs Corporation introduced the D825 in 1962, a four-processor computer that accessed up to 16 memory modules through a crossbar switch.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1967, Amdahl and Slotnick published a debate about the feasibility of parallel processing at American Federation of Information Processing Societies Conference.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] It was during this debate that Amdahl's law was coined to define the limit of speed-up due to parallelism.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1969, Honeywell introduced its first Multics system, a symmetric multiprocessor system capable of running up to eight processors in parallel.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] C.mmp, a multi-processor project at Carnegie Mellon University in the 1970s, was among the first multiprocessors with more than a few processors.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The first bus-connected multiprocessor with snooping caches was the Synapse N+1 in 1984.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] SIMD parallel computers can be traced back to the 1970s.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The motivation behind early SIMD computers was to amortize the gate delay of the processor's control unit over multiple instructions.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1964, Slotnick had proposed building a massively parallel computer for the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] His design was funded by the US Air Force, which was the earliest SIMD parallel-computing effort, ILLIAC IV.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The key to its design was a fairly high parallelism, with up to 256 processors, which allowed the machine to work on large datasets in what would later be known as vector processing.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] However, ILLIAC IV was called "the most infamous of supercomputers", because the project was only one-fourth completed, but took 11 years and cost almost four times the original estimate.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] When it was finally ready to run its first real application in 1976, it was outperformed by existing commercial supercomputers such as the Cray-1.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In the early 1970s, at the MIT Computer Science and Artificial Intelligence Laboratory, Marvin Minsky and Seymour Papert started developing the *Society of Mind* theory, which views the biological brain as massively parallel computer.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] In 1986, Minsky published *The Society of Mind*, which claims that "mind is formed from many little agents, each mindless by itself".
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] The theory attempts to explain how what we call intelligence could be a product of the interaction of non-intelligent parts.
[src:dask-parallel/parallel-computing] Minsky says that the biggest source of ideas about the theory came from his work in trying to create a machine that uses a robotic arm, a video camera, and a computer to build with children's blocks.
